sentences: Walter Davis Jr. (September 2, 1932 – June 2, 1990) was an American hard bop pianist.
He played with Max Roach and Charlie Parker, recording with Roach in 1953.
He joined Dizzy Gillespie’s band in 1956, and toured the Middle East and South America.
He also played in Paris with Donald Byrd in 1958 and with Art Blakey & the Jazz Messengers in 1959.
He also played in Paris with Donald Byrd in 1958 and with Art Blakey & the Jazz Messengers in 1959.
He studied music in India in 1979, and played with Sonny Rollins in the early ’70s.
In the 1950s, Davis recorded with Melba Liston, Max Roach and played with Roach, Charlie Parker, and Dizzy Gillespie.
In 1958 he played with trumpeter Donald Byrd at Le Chat Qui Pêche in Paris and shortly after realized his dream of becoming pianist and composer-arranger for Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers.
After retiring from music in the 1960s to work as a tailor, painter, and designer, he returned in the 1970s to perform with Sonny Rollins and again with the Jazz Messengers.
After retiring from music in the 1960s to work as a tailor, painter, and designer, he returned in the 1970s to perform with Sonny Rollins and again with the Jazz Messengers.
He also contributed to the soundtrack of the Clint Eastwood film Bird (1988).
Davis died in New York City on June 2, 1990, from complications of liver and kidney disease.
